    <article class="card block">
      <h2 class="title" style="color:var(--accent)">1-minute cone method (no stress)</h2>
      <ol style="margin:0;padding-left:18px">
        <li><strong>Grind medium-fluffy.</strong> Not powder. Tiny stems out.</li>
        <li><strong>Create a “funnel.”</strong> Pinch the cone open; rest it in a shot glass or cone holder.</li>
        <li><strong>Load in thirds.</strong> Sprinkle, then <em>tap the filter on the table</em> to settle.</li>
        <li><strong>Tamp lightly.</strong> Use a straw, packing tool, or the cone’s stick—gentle pressure.</li>
        <li><strong>Twist and toast.</strong> Twist the tip shut. Spin the end near a flame to pre-seal the edge; then light.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Roll clinic (90 seconds):</strong> small crutch, don’t overpack the tip, tap &amp; spin to settle, twist gently,
        and toast the edge before first draw. If it canoes, lick the fast side lightly and roll between fingers—like ironing a tiny shirt.
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

